more efficient, and transparent digital tools is what motivated us to build We‚Äôre zero waste experts and data people, and our goal is to deliver a waste operations platform that makes it easier for businesses to recycle more, divert materials from landfills and incinerators, and reduce their impacts on our social and natural The Team Laura Rosenshine (she her) CEO Laura founded Common Ground Compost LLC (CGC) after a few years working in the commercial waste sector, including working with a technology company piloting organics processing in In , Laura Foodprint Group which was focused on bringing standardization and industry best practices to the waste management programs of hospitality and food In , Laura returned to CGC to focus on building a Laura is a TRUE Certified Waste Meredith (she her) Executive Director Meredith is the Executive Director of Common Ground Compost She sits on the US Composting Council board of directors and the steering committee of the Institute for Local Self Reliance‚Äôs Community Composting She believes that materials literacy and upstream downstream supply chain transparency are foundational building blocks to the circular Meredith is a TRUE Certified Waste William Klimpert (he him) Director of Analytics William Klimpert is the Director of Analytics at Common Ground As an avid nature enthusiast with a background in plant biophysics, he seeks to use data and technology to increase the accessibility of sustainability Since , William has been working with CGC to develop tools and reports that improve workflows and bring audit, composting, and diversion statistics to William is a TRUE Certified Waste Annabella Mineghino (she her) Product Manager A California native currently based in Prague, Annabella applies global learning OPERATIONS All businesses generate Waste streams are the foundation of WATS organizes all stakeholders that handle, organize, and manage waste WATS: Centralizes information related to a company‚Äôs waste streams, and automatically creates a digital waste management plan and easily shareable standard operating Connects waste generators with vendors that can deliver services for maximum diversion from Delivers waste reduction ROI planning and analysis REPORTING Businesses need to report on the impacts of their WATS: Standardizes data from various vendors for ESG reports Automates carbon footprint reporting (EPA WARM model as a baseline) Builds specific waste metrics analysis Visualizes roll up comparisons for sites across portfolios Simplifies waste cost analysis and anomaly identification REGULATIONS Legislation is changing as a result of climate WATS: Flags non compliance with local waste policies Prepares businesses for evolving reporting standards Transform your standard waste streams from these - To include specialty waste streams like these (with variations based on entity type) - divert valuable materials from landfills and track your impact! Google - Net Zero by - Bend Skip to Content Sign In Google @ Google GOOGL Total Emissions Intensity Net Zero by Google commits to Net Zero emissions by . They announced this commitment on Sep , . More from Google How to read this chart The Emissions Chart displays the selected company‚Äôs reported and forecasted greenhouse gas emissions, all measured in ‚Äòmetric tons of carbon dioxide equivalents‚Äô ( CO2e ). Reported Emissions are at the top left, in blue . Reported Emissions cover a company‚Äôs entire carbon footprint ‚Äî both direct and supply chain Purchased Offsets are at the bottom left, in red . Purchased Offsets cover all verified carbon removal credits ‚Äî reforestation, direct air capture, Forecasted Emissions are at the top right, in green . Bend estimates these emissions according to a company‚Äôs sustainability commitments, listed below the chart (and assuming steady progress towards those targets). Forecasted Offsets are at the bottom right, in yellow . Bend estimates the amount of offsets a company will need to achieve their targets, defaulting to a 50 split between emissions reductions and purchased offsets (the less that companies rely on offsets, the better). The Intensity Chart (right tab) measures a company‚Äôs annual net emissions against their annual revenue (a useful measure to understand the CO2e impact of every dollar spent with a given company). Intensity projections are currently calculated by assuming revenue growth equal to that since the climate commitment was If revenue declined since the commitment was announced, or if only one year of revenue data is available, revenue is assumed to be Why you should be skeptical of this data It‚Äôs wise to take this data with a grain of Companies have an incentive to undercount their emissions, and overcount Offsets in particular warrant In the past, the claimed climate benefits of offsets have often been Offsets are necessary ‚Äî there don‚Äôt yet exist ways to fully decarbonize every business activity ‚Äî but we need to ratchet up the rigor and verifiability of What emissions are included? The data reported here is intended to reflect a company‚Äôs total carbon footprint, as defined by the Greenhouse Gas Protocol ‚Äî the global standard for carbon The Greenhouse Gas Protocol covers three categories of emissions: Scope 1: direct emissions from something you own (e.g. burning natural gas to heat a building driving a vehicle that burns gasoline). Scope 2: the carbon footprint of your purchased electricity (e.g. the coal or natural gas burned to power your office, warehouse, ). Scope 3: Everything else, up and down your supply From the manufacturing and transportation of your products, to the goods and services you purchase, to your business travel and commuting, to the downstream usage and disposal of your For most companies, Scope 3 accounts for the majority of For that reason, Bend only tracks companies who disclose their full emissions (Scope 1, 2, & 3). What qualifies as a Net Zero commitment? Companies that set Net Zero targets (according to the Science Based Targets initiative) commit to first deeply reducing their emissions, and then purchasing enough offsets to cover the The only valid Net Zero commitments (and the only commitments published here) cover a company‚Äôs entire footprint, including all supply chain Learn more . Scaler - Preparing for future success Request a demo Log in Jan , | 3 min read Preparing for future success Sacha van Tuijn This blog post has been updated on February A recent update to the GRESB website has amended the timeline for scoring intensities, although it still shows clear support for recognizing performance: "Moving towards a better recognition of performance is one of the top priorities for GRESB over the next couple of " Scoring intensities would mean a big change, one that needs the appropriate time and involvement of the industry to undertake GRESB is not confining itself to a precise timeline at the moment, and rightly so: "This transition to real performance assessment will begin with the start of scoring intensities in the " But beyond benchmarking and reporting, looking at intensities remains critical to assessing one s portfolio to inform investment Original post: A new year comes with new beginnings, one of which is annual reporting like Although the GRESB Portal doesn‚Äôt open until April , managers and consultants across the globe are starting to think about GRESB and the savvy ones are already beginning to collect their From year to year, GRESB usually only makes incremental changes to the They might tweak some answer options or add new questions they are testing out but won‚Äôt This year, changes will be found around net zero, physical climate risk and transition risk, and diversity, equity and inclusion, designed to reflect the increasing importance of these A detailed list of the changes can be found here , and indeed, a quick look will show that most of changes won‚Äôt be scored or otherwise have an impact on You can also already find the Real Estate Reference Guide here ‚Äî it s a key resource for GRESB Managers should be focusing on how to improve and streamline their data collection processes for GRESB and other reporting And while everyone would like to see an improvement on their score year on year, at this point, this can only be achieved by reporting correctly and reflecting actual improvement in That is to say, there aren t any actions that can be taken now to improve last year s So while managers are putting resources toward collecting data and reporting correctly, it is also a key moment to invest resources in improving performance in in order to prepare for reporting next year . There is a particular urgency to improve performance this Attention is being focused on ESG like never before mandatory and voluntary reporting frameworks are being developed and adopted around the globe and our global and sector carbon budgets are lower due to emissions overshoot the past couple of And, starting in , we can expect bigger changes to the GRESB Real Estate Assessment: with the development of their roadmap, GRESB has laid the groundwork to shift the Assessment to be more In their own words, one of the top priorities over the next couple of years is, Moving towards a better recognition of performance‚Ä¶ This transition to real performance assessment will begin with the start of scoring intensities as of . You can find this information and answers to other important questions here . Currently, the Energy Aspect accounts for % of the score, comprised of Indicators for energy data coverage, change, and renewable We don‚Äôt have more detail yet on how intensities will be scored, but somewhere within the formula, energy intensity could count toward point Energy use intensity is calculate by dividing the total energy consumed by the total gross floor area and is often normalized by factors like occupancy It gets at the heart of building performance more accurately than just data coverage, change and renewable energy So what does this mean? Well, it probably means that we can expect a drop in scores as scoring becomes more rigorous with these new The GRESB Assessment and scoring model hasn‚Äôt seen this much change since , when average scores saw a decrease (for the first and only time). It was also marked by much displeasure throughout the industry, which relies upon GRESB Scores for a number of things, including communicating ESG performance to investors, and generally expects to see scores increase year over year to reflect their improved ESG While we don‚Äôt know the precise nature of the changes for , knowing that intensities will be scored does allow us to factor them into strategy this In the Scaler platform, we provide clients with a GRESB dashboard that fully aligns with the Asset level Spreadsheet to streamline reporting and make the Performance Component much easier to We estimate points received for indicators according to the GRESB Scoring model, so that clients have an idea of how they will score long before they In addition, we provide clients with a more rigorous Scaler Score which already takes intensities into account . Each asset is scored, giving precise insight into which are underperforming and how each contributes to the GRESB Score and our Scaler In this way, we empower managers

million people worldwide are confronted with the fact that they cannot have children without IVF . However IVF is accessible to barely 1% of those worldwide who need If all intended parents were able to access IVF, million babies would be born annually rather than the present 1 million . Why are most infertile adults unable to access IVF care? The core of the problem are the manual, analog, ‚Äúartisanal‚Äù IVF labs which, without exception, have remained largely unchanged since the birth of the first IVF child over years Current IVF labs are inefficient, expensive, often error prone and impossible to THE SOLUTION At Conceivable, we believe in the power of children‚Äîand helping millions more people access IVF in order to fulfill their dreams of becoming We‚Äôre creating automation for the next generation of IVF, designing labs with the most advanced single cell robotics in the Conceivable‚Äôs labs will provide vastly more safety, efficiency, and scalability‚Äîso that everyone who needs IVF can access The good news? Pipeline | Altesa BioSciences Home Leadership Opportunity Impact Pipeline News News Releases Media Coverage Contact Pipeline Altesa‚Äôs pipeline of drug candidates stops the viruses‚Äô abilities to replicate in the human If viruses can‚Äôt replicate, their abilities to cause organ damage and death are Altesa‚Äôs goal is to stop the viruses before they seriously harm vulnerable Vapendavir , a capsid inhibitor (prevents the virus from entering human cells and also prevents the virus from reproducing) with potent activity across all rhinoviruses and other respiratory enteroviruses, is our most advanced pipeline Altesa has exclusive global rights to develop, manufacture, and commercialize This modern antiviral treatment, which is taken in pill form, is in Phase 2 clinical It has been with positive antiviral data in human trials in over Altesa also has exclusive rights to develop new treatments emerging from the laboratories of Emory University, working seamlessly with academic and Altesa‚Äôs first molecule from Emory is This exciting new drug is a nucleoside analog (prevents effective viral replication), active against most enteroviruses (including rhinoviruses causing the common cold, and other viruses leading to deadly infections in children), and flaviviruses (causing dengue, yellow fever, encephalitis, Zika, and other serious illnesses). BioSciences, All rights reserved   Impact | Altesa BioSciences Home Leadership Opportunity Impact Pipeline News News Releases Media Coverage Contact Impact All of us have experienced viral infections such as the common cold, the flu, and perhaps even Fortunately, most viruses cause no damage to our health, but many common viruses‚Äîeven the ‚Äúcommon cold‚Äù virus‚Äîcan be deadly, or cause health consequences among vulnerable Tens of millions of Americans are at risk of health effects, and even death, from these These include people living with chronic lung diseases, cancer, bone marrow transplants, immature or compromised immune systems (e.g., neonates, those with HIV infections), or other health For these individuals, a simple case of the sniffles can turn into pneumonia, a blood stream or brain infection, or ‚Äúpolio-like‚Äù paralysis, in which infection can lead to critical organ damage or failure, and possibly even Globally, thousands of adults and children die each year from viral diseases like dengue, yellow and West Nile fevers, and Altesa will change this For millions of vulnerable people, a cold is never ‚Äújust a ‚Äù Up to half of all upper respiratory tract infections (e.g., the ‚Äúcommon cold‚Äù) are caused by rhinoviruses, a subset of the picornavirus These viruses can cause hepatitis, Ebola disease, mouth, SARS, influenza, polio, measles, AIDS, , and many other debilitating or deadly Collectively, these viruses are responsible for a large burden of disease around the Effective antivirals are needed to treat vulnerable infected or exposed individuals, because viruses are so In addition, they mutate so frequently that vaccinations are effective against only a small minority of these People at High Risk Include: The elderly, especially those in long term care Adults and children with lung diseases like Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) and asthma People with compromised immune systems (natural or acquired), including those undergoing solid organ or stem cell transplants or cancer treatments, neonates, and those with HIV AIDS People with other conditions who are on therapies that suppress or dampen the immune response, for example, to treat disorders like rheumatoid arthritis and Those with certain serious underlying health The Promise of Vapendavir Viral infections causing the common cold are difficult to Even people who work hard to avoid getting sick, like those with COPD, suffer, on average, more than one cold per year, which can lead to a dangerous loss of lung function, and even Altesa is developing a new treatment to prevent loss of lung function by directly stopping the virus from multiplying in the Today‚Äôs new generation of highly sensitive and easily accessible diagnostic tests can catch viral infections at their earliest In vulnerable people, early diagnosis and treatment provide an opportunity to stop viruses in their tracks‚Äîbefore they can damage lungs and many other This is the future of medicine: preventing downstream outcomes resulting from uncontrolled viral Leadership Opportunity Impact Pipeline News Contact Expanded Access Policy Altesa BioSciences, Harvard
